reason: >
  The user-facing surface this change touches is a one-line re-key of the
  cockpit's reopen call — it now passes the change's unique id instead of the
  non-unique 6-char handle. There is no new screen, flow, or interaction
  surface to drive; the behaviour is a backend identity-resolution change with
  a single-line cockpit consumer.

  The user-observable outcome — reopening a tidied change whose handle is
  shared rebuilds ITS OWN workspace, never a sibling's, and an ambiguous
  handle refuses with a candidate list — is already verified comprehensively in
  test form:
    - the cockpit unit test asserts the reopen request carries the exact
      change_id and never the handle (recreate-on-demand HD-004);
    - the collision regression drives all four act-on verbs (recreate / focus /
      ship / nuke) against the live 26-collision shape (one handle shared by
      four changes), asserting each resolves to itself and the shared handle
      refuses with a four-candidate list;
    - the Hypothesis property suite proves the resolution invariants
      universally over generated collision shapes (each proven to catch the
      original bug when re-injected);
    - the stateful lifecycle model drives random start/ship/nuke/recreate/focus
      sequences and asserts after every step that no verb ever acts on the
      wrong id.

  Authoring and browser-driving a full cockpit user-journey scenario is
  disproportionate for a one-line consumer change with no new flow, and would
  land as manual-attest (no standing cockpit in CI). Exemption recorded by the
  founder at the ship gate.
